To retrieve cookies from a client's browser, you would typically use the `HttpServletRequest` object to get the value of the `Cookie` object associated with the cookie name. The `HttpServletResponse` object is used to set the response headers that contain the cookie values.

Here's an example of how you might retrieve and set cookie values in a servlet:

```java
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletResponse;

public class CookieServlet extends HttpServlet {
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) throws ServletException, IOException {
        // Get the value of the 'name' attribute from the request
        String name = request.getParameter("name");

        // Set the value of the 'name' attribute in the response
        response.addCookie(new Cookie(name, "value"));
    }
}
```

In this example, `request.getParameter("name")` retrieves the value of the cookie with the name specified in the URL. The `response.addCookie()` method sets the cookie to be sent back to the client.

